\title{Measurement of inclusive jet production and nuclear modifications in pPb collisions at $\sqrtsNN=5.02\TeV$}











\date{\today}


\abstract{
Inclusive jet production in pPb collisions at a nucleon-nucleon (NN) center-of-mass energy of $\sqrtsNN=5.02\TeV$ is studied with the CMS detector at the LHC. A data sample corresponding to an integrated luminosity of 35\nbinv is analyzed.
The jet transverse momentum spectra are studied in seven  pseudorapidity intervals covering  the range $ -2.0 <\eta_\mathrm{CM}< 1.5$ in  the NN center-of-mass frame. The jet production yields at forward and backward  pseudorapidity are compared and  no significant asymmetry about $\eta_\mathrm{CM} = 0$  is observed in the measured kinematic range. The measurements in the pPb system are compared to reference jet spectra obtained by extrapolation from previous measurements in pp collisions  at  $\sqrt{s}=7\TeV$. In all pseudorapidity ranges, nuclear modifications in inclusive jet production are found to be small, similar to the predictions from next-to-leading order perturbative QCD calculations that incorporate nuclear effects in the parton distribution functions.
}

